# Supporting functions

The purposes of these functions are for supporting when working with R and RStudio as well as for formatting outputs from other functions of data managment and analysis. 

## Clean your workspace 

The foremost thing you should do when starting an R session is clear your workspace as R somtimes tends to save your previous work. You do not want your current project to be confused with your last ones.   

The `clear()` function clean three places: Global Envionment, Console and Plots. It does not require any argument.   

```{r Clean your workspace, eval=FALSE}
# loading the package 
library(mStats)
# clean workspace
clear()
```

## Logging your console outputs 

You usually do this in R by using `sink()` function. It has two caveats. 

1. You cannot both run and save the console outputs at the same time. It can be forcibly obtained using `split` argument. 
2. Only outputs will be saved, but not commands. If you want to save commands, you can source the file by setting `echo = TRUE`. But there is also anther problem where your modelling commands sometimes produce error message, which stops the sourcing process. 

To counter this and also inspired by STATA's `log` command, `ilog()` function comes in very handy. A log file is created by two processes: opening a text connection to our log file and closing it.   


```{r Logging your console outputs, echo=TRUE}
# Open the log file
ilog("~/R/myFirstLog.txt", append = FALSE)

# load iris dataset 
data(iris)
# Check data structure, its summary measures 
str(iris)
summary(iris)

# Close log file
ilog.close()
```





