# Functions for data management 

Data management, sometimes known as data processing, is an important aspect of data analysis workflow. Skillful data managment is essential to efficient workflow. 

## Viewing the dataset 

R has built-in function `View()` for this purpose. If it is called, it opens a new spread-sheet like window. As a more convenient counterpart, `listView()` lists several variables of desire and display the values.   

```{r}
# listview variables of infert data
listView(infert, education:stratum)

# listview selected variables
listView(infert, c(education, case, stratum))
```

## Describing the dataset or codebook

The `codebook` or its alias `describe()` provides the following information about the variables. 

1. `VARS_NAME`: variable's name 
2. `LABEL`: variable's label 
3. `DATA_TYPE`: data type 
4. `OBS_COUNT`: Number of Observations
5. `NA_COUNT`: Number of missing values (NA)
6. `NA_(%)`: Percentage of missing values (NA)
   
      
```{r codebook}
# codebook of iris dataset
codebook(iris)
```

## Handling duplicated data

Finding duplicated records comes in very handy. Visually inspecting the dataset makes us almost impossible to spot duplications particularly if there is no unique ID for each records or the dataset is large.     

The `duplicates()` function finds duplicated records by given variales or all variables (if such is not specified) and serially tags the records by creating a new variable `dupID_` intended for future uses. It produces a nice report of duplicated observations and surplus copies which is inspired by `STATA`'s `duplicates` command.   

```{r duplicates}
# finding duplicated records in iris dataset
iris_dup <- duplicates(iris)
# check data structure
str(iris_dup)
```

Another advantage is that the function returns a data.frame so further processing can be pursued.   

There are two more functions that either keep or remove only duplicated records. 

* `keepUnique`: remove all duplicated records, making the dataset unique. 
* `keepDup`: keep all duplicated records   

   

```{r keepUnique & keepDup}
# remove duplciated records
keepUnique(iris, Species)
str(keepUnique(iris, Sepal.Length))


# keep duplicated records
str(keepDup(iris, Sepal.Length))
```


