## Creating and transforming variables

In most cases, the variables in the orginal datasets may not be what we need for data analysis. Hence, we either need to create new variables or edit existing ones by combining or transforming other variables.    


   
### generate()

This basic command `generate` can be used to create variables by performing arithmetic or logical operations on existing variables. It then  returns a new data.frame containing the newly created variable.   

Below we will create a new variable called `age.grp` from `age` of `infert` dataset. First, we will check its summary measures. Then, based on its mean value, we will split into two groups: one group where `age` is less than mean and the other one where it is greater than or equal to the mean.    

Note the notification shown after running the `generate` command, indicating how many values have been created and the expression used to create this. 

```{r generate}
# check age of infert dataset
summary(infert$age)
# generate age.grp based on mean value 
infert_age <- generate(infert, age.grp, as.numeric(age < 31.50))
# check what's been created
str(infert_age)
```


The example demonstrated above is quite easy and that's is not usually how we want our `age.grp`. Now, we will try to split age group into 5 groups: <= 25, 26-30, 31-35, 36-40, >40.   

We can use this function with the help of `ifelse` function.  

```{r generate2}
# create age.grp into 5 categories
infert_age5 <- generate(infert, age.grp, 
         ifelse(age <= 25, 1, 
                ifelse(age > 25 & age <= 30, 2, 
                       ifelse(age > 30 & age <= 35, 3, 
                              ifelse(age > 35 & age <= 40, 4, 
                                     ifelse(age > 40, 5, NA))))))
# check what's been created
str(infert_age5)
# tabulate age.grp 
tab(infert_age5$age.grp)
```


\newpage
### egen()

The example shown above is somewhat tedious to type several `ifelse` statements. To ease it to a certain extent, we can use another function `egen` to cut down a numeric variable into a categorical one.    

This `egen` function is an extended version of `generate` function where you can easily convert a dataset's variable into categorical one. You can specify the cut-points and corresponding labels as well as the name your variable will be created into. If you don't specify, the function will automatically do for you. Read the documentation for details.   

Let's use the same example as above. 

```{r egen}
# generate age.grp by using egen
infert_egen <- egen(infert, age, cut = c(26, 31, 36, 41), 
     lbl = c("<=25", "26-30", "31-35", "36-40", "41+"), 
     new.var = age.grp)
# tabulate age.grp
tab(age.grp, infert_egen)
```


This function also lets us know how many values has been generated.   

The result from this tabulation output is the same as above, but the command is simpler. But the downside is that it can be used only for transforming numeric data to categorical ones. 


\newpage
### recode()

Often variables in original datasets have to be coded into the values we want. This usually happens when there are too many categories or without meaningful values.   

With the function `recode`, we can recode all values of a variable in one single step. 
From our `infert` dataset, we will recode `case` from 0 and 1 to 2 and 3.     

```{r recode1}
# check case variable 
tab(case, infert)
# recoding 0 and 1 to 2 and 3
infert_recode <- recode(infert, case, c(0, 1), c(2, 3))
# check recoded case variable 
tab(case, infert_recode)
```


Here, the function also lets us know which values are coded into which ones.   

Next, we will use the same variable but recode the numeric values into characters, from 0 and 1 to "No" and "Yes".   

```{r recode2}
# recoding 0 and 1 to No and Yes
infert_recode <- recode(infert, case, c(0, 1), c("No", "Yes"))
# check recoded case variable 
tab(case, infert_recode)
```

   
