## Labels

Labels are usually attached to the corresponding variables to provide additional information about variables, either the meaning of the variable itself (variable label) or the meaning of the values of the variable (value labels).    

### Variable labels

Variable labels are used to expand the meaning of a variable beyond its name so that anyone can understand the meaning of variables used. We use `labelVars` to label variables.   

In this function, `data` argument is optional, which means that you can label vectors.

Let's label `age` from `infert` dataset as `Age of patients`.   

```{r labelVars1}
# label age
infert_ageLabel <- labelVars(infert, age, "age of patient")
# summarize age 
summ(age, infert_ageLabel)
```


Let's create a vector `x` and assign the label `dummy label`.    

```{r labelVars2}
# create a vector x
x <- 1:100 
# label x as dummy label 
x <- labelVars(NULL, x, "dummy label")
# summarize x 
summ(x)
```


    
This time we will label multiple variables at the same time. 

```{r labelVars3}
# label multiple variables at the same time. 
infert_multiLabel <- labelVars(
    infert, 
    c(education, age, parity, induced, case), 
    c("Patient's education in years", "Patient's age in Years", 
      "Count of pregnancy", "Number of Induced abortions", 
      "Case Status: 1 case and 0 control")
)
# check the labels 
codebook(infert_multiLabel)
```

     
     
### Dataset labels

Datasets can be labelled so that it provides more meaningful information. It's also known as meta-data of the dataset.     

Let's label the `infert` dataset. 

```{r labelData}
# Labelling the dataset 
infert_label <- labelData(infert,
        "Infertility after Spontaneous and Induced Abortion")
# Check the label 
codebook(infert_label)
```


\newpage
### Value labels

Value labels give text descriptions to the numerical values of a variable. In R, this is equivalent to a factor variable. We can easily convert other data types into factors as well as changes their categories.     

The order of the categories depend on the sequence appeared during tabulation. 

```{r labelValues1}
# check tabulation sequence
tab(case, infert)
# label values of case into no and yes 
infert_case <- labelValues(infert, case, c("No", "Yes"))
# check tabulation again
tab(case, infert_case)
```

     
Similar to previous functions, it also allows value labelling of multiple variables.   

Let's label case as No and Yes, induced as none, one and two, education as low, mide and high, at the same time.    

```{r labelValues2}
# check tabulation sequence
tab(c(case, induced, education), infert)
# label them at the same time
infert_new <- labelValues(
    infert, 
    list(case, induced, education), 
    list(c("No", "Yes"), 
         c("None", "One", "Two"), 
         c("Low", "Mid", "High"))
)
# check tab again
tab(c(case, induced, education), infert_new)
```


