## Subsetting Data

Often your original dataset is big with hundreds of variables and tens of thousands of observations. In such cases, you can `keep` or `lose` **variables** of interest as well as `pick` **observations** of interest, in order to make the dataset small enough for you to manage.     

These functions return the changed dataset that can be assigned for further processing. They also display the notification about changes being made, which is a nice feature of this package.    


### keep() or lose()

Sometimes you do not want all of the variables in a data file. You can use the `keep` and `lose` functions to subset variables.

If we think of your data like a spreadsheet, this will show how you can remove variables from your data. Let’s try this with the `infert` dataset.   

```{r keep}
# keep three variables: education, age and parity
str(keep(infert, education, age, parity))
# lose education and case 
str(lose(infert, education, case, parity, stratum, pooled.stratum))
```

These showed how to use `keep` and `lose` variables to remove variables from your dataset.    
 
 
### pick()

Next, the function `pick` can be used to keep and drop observations. Thinking of your data like a spreadsheet, `pick` can be used to remove rows of your data.

```{r pick}
# we want age between 30 and 40. 
infert_age <- pick(infert, age >= 30 & age <= 40)
# check the summary 
summ(age, infert_age)
```


### arrange()

This function arranges the order of observations based on the combination of several variables. Putting negative sign `-` in front of the variables will arrange observations in descending order and if nothing is specified, it will be in ascending order.     

```{r arrange}
# arrange by age in ascending order
head(arrange(infert, age))
# by descending order 
head(arrange(infert, -age))
# mixed order of several variables
head(arrange(infert, age, education, -case))
```

Also note the notification.    



