## Formating Dates

This set of functions deals with `Date` format in R.    

### is.Date()

As very simple as it is, the function to check whether an object is of `Date` data type is missing in base R.

```{r is.Date}
# Creating a Date vector
x <- as.Date(c("2020-01-01", "2020-01-02", "2020-01-03", 
               "2020-01-04", "2020-01-05"), format = "%Y-%m-%d")
# check its type
typeof(x)
# check whether it is a Date format
is.Date(x)
```


### day(), month(), year()

Similar to the previous one, base R does not provide functions to extract days or months or years from Dates.    

```{r day month year}
# Creating a Date vector
x <- as.Date(c("2020-01-01", "2020-01-02", "2020-01-03", 
               "2020-01-04", "2020-01-05"), format = "%Y-%m-%d")
# extract years
year(x)
# extract months
month(x)
# extract days
day(x)
```


### formatDate()

Often Date variables are read from original dataset as either characters or numbers. In this case, `formatDate` can quickly convert these into Dates.     

First, let's convert some characters into Dates. 

```{r formatDate Characters}
# creating a character vector
y <- c("2019-01-15", "2019-01-20", "2019-01-21", "2019-01-22")
# check if y is a Date
is.Date(y)
# change to Dates
y.dates <- formatDate(y, "Ymd", "-")
# check if y.dates is a Date
is.Date(y.dates)
```


Next, we will convert numbers to Dates.    

```{r formatDate Numbers}
# creating numeric vector 
y <- 42705: 42805
# convert to Dates
y.dates <- formatDate(y)
y.dates
# check if y.dates is Date
is.Date(y.dates)
```



