# Functions for Data Analysis

This domain is regarded with activities taken after getting the final clean data. It can be further separated into three sets of functions. 

1. Epidemiological analysis 
2. Exploratory data analysis 
3. Formatting outputs of Modelling


## Epidemiological analysis

This set of functions are intended to help in epidemiological calculations.  

### Calculating Incidence Rates `strate`

Rates of event occurrences, known as incidence rates are outcome measures in longitudinal studies. In most longitudinal studies, follow-up times vary due to logistic resasons, different periods of recruitment, delay enrolment into the study, lost-to-follow-up, immigration or emigration and death.   

**Follow-up time in longitudinal studies**    

Period of observation (called as follow-up time) starts when individuals join the study and ends when they either have an outcome of interest, are lost-to- follow-up or the follow-up period ends, whichever happens first. This period is called person-year-at-risk. This is denoted by PY in strate function's output and numer of event by D.   

The function `strate` calculates Incidence Rates per population as well as its 95% confidence intervals. The calculation can also be stratified by another variable.     

The following demonstrates two examples of calculating stratified  incidence rates: by sex and age groups.   

In the first example, sex is recoded into male and female and then the analysis is performed.     

In the second example, age groups are created by uisng `egen` function based on 51, 61, and 71 cut-off points. Then incidence rates are calculated.    

```{r incidence rate}
# load survival library to access lung data
library(survival)
data(lung)
# check data structure
str(lung)
# codebook the data
codebook(lung)


## incidence rates
strate(lung, time, status, per = 100)
# faliure event can be specified
strate(lung, time, status, fail = 2, per = 1000)

# recoding sex 
lung <- recode(lung, sex, c(1, 2), c("Male", "Female"))
# check cross-tabulation
xtab(sex, status, lung)
## incidence rates stratified by sex
strate(lung, time, status, by = sex, per = 1000)

# summarize age 
summ(age, lung)
# getting age.grp into 4 groups
lung <- egen(lung, age, c(51, 61, 71), 
             c("<=50", "51-60", "61-70", "71+"), age.grp)
# check cross-tabulation 
xtab(age.grp, status, lung)
## incidence rates stratified by age.grp
strate(lung, time, status, by = age.grp, per = 1000)

```


