## Exploratory Data analysis

After data mangement, exploring data is all about understanding your data. Sometimes this is called descriptive or summary measures. That means it depends on the nature and type of the data. 

### One-way tabulation 

Frequency distribution is the most common summary measure for categorical data, either nominal or ordinal data. With `tab`, tabulation of either one variable, several variables or the whole dataset becomes very easy.    

Let's find the frequency distribution of variables from `esoph` dataset. 

```{r tab1}
# data esoph
str(esoph)
# tabulation of agegp 
tab(agegp, esoph)
# one-way tabulation of agegp, alcgph, tobgp
tab(c(agegp, alcgp, tobgp), esoph)
# one-way tab of esoph
tab(esoph)
```


### Cross-tabulation 

Exploring data is without cross-examing between two variables. When tabulating two categorical data, `xtab` comes in very handy. It can either simply cross-tab two variables or cross-tab between a numeric and a categorical data if both are treated as categorical data, or even cross-tab the whole dataset by a variable.     

Let's try these with `esoph` dataset.    

```{r tab2}
# cross-tab agegp and alcgp
xtab(agegp, alcgp, esoph)
# cross-tab ncases and agegp 
xtab(ncases, agegp, esoph)
# cross-tab the whole dataset by agegp 
xtab(esoph, agegp)
```


### Number Summary

There are several number summary measures. However, `summ` function handpicks a set of commonly used measures and displays in a well-formatted manner. These measures include 

1. Obs: Number of Observation 
2. NA: Number of missing data (NA)
3. Mean: Arithmetic average
4. Std.Dev: Standard Deviation 
5. Median: Median, 50% Quantile (Q50) 
6. Q1: 25% Quantile (Q1)
7. Q3: 75% Quantile (Q3) 
8. Min: Minimum
9. Max: Maximum 
10. CV: Coefficient of Variation, (SD / Mean) * 100
11. Normal.test: Shapiro-Wilk Normality Test

    
This function also lets you summarize one variable, several variables or the whole dataset. 

Let's summarize `infert` dataset.    

```{r summ}
# summary measure of age
summ(age, infert)
# summary measure of age, parity, induced, case
summ(c(age, parity, induced, case), infert)
# summary measure of infert
summ(infert)
```


### Grouped Summary Measures

Summary measures can be disaggregated by a categorical variable. With `summBy` function, p values from tests such as student's t-test and ANOVA test based on number of groups will be automatically displayed along with some important summary measures. These summary measures are relatively fewer, compared to the outputs from `summ`.    

Similar to previous functions, `summBy` can also be used with two variables as well as summarization of the whole dataset by a categorical data.    

Let's demonstrate with `infert` dataset. 

```{r summBy}
# summary measures of age by education 
summBy(age, education, infert)
# summary measures of several variables by education 
summBy(c(age, parity, induced), education, infert)
# wummary measures of the whole dataset by case 
summBy(infert, case)
```




